post_text:
Good morning,

At Stokes School the safety and well-being of our students and staff is always our top priority. As we have watched the spread of the Coronavirus (COVID-19) in the United States over the past few weeks, we have also been developing contingency plans for the possibility of closing our campuses. In accordance with guidance from the Mayor of the District of Columbia’s office, the Elsie Whitlow Stokes Community Freedom Public Charter School will close beginning Monday, March 16th and remain closed through at least March 31st.

As we have previously communicated, Stokes School’s teachers and instructional staff are compiling materials that will facilitate student learning at home while our campuses are closed. We will provide specific information on how to access these materials in a subsequent communication with families.

Stokes School will continue to follow the guidance of federal and city government officials to determine when the school will re-open. We appreciate your cooperation and will keep you updated as soon as decisions are made.

Please be safe.

post_text:
Preparing for a Potential Coronavirus Outbreak

Dear Stokes School Community,

We are working to maintain a safe, healthy environment within our school community. We reiterate daily with staff and scholars the importance of:
• proper hand washing;
• avoiding touching eyes, noses and mouths;
• sneezing/coughing in elbows or tissue; and
• staying at home when we are ill.
Additionally, our cleaning company follows CDC recommendations for cleaning and disinfecting our buildings.

Despite these steps, there may still be a Coronavirus outbreak in Washington, DC. We are preparing for the possibility that the DC government may close the schools.

As we plan, we are working to ensure that staff has remote access to work and that scholars have access to learning. We ask that you complete the brief survey sent through the listserv about your children's access to technology at home.

To have adequate time to prepare, we ask that families submit responses by 5:00 pm on Tuesday, March 9th. Please feel free to reach out to any school administrator if you have questions.

• proper hand washing;
• avoiding touching eyes, noses and mouths;
• sneezing/coughing in elbows or tissue; and
• staying at home when we are ill.
Additionally, our cleaning company follows CDC recommendations for cleaning and disinfecting our buildings.

Despite these steps, there may still be a Coronavirus outbreak in Washington, DC. We are preparing for the possibility that the DC government may close the schools.

As we plan, we are working to ensure that staff has remote access to work and that scholars have access to learning. We ask that you complete the brief survey sent through the listserv about your children's access to technology at home.

To have adequate time to prepare, we ask that families submit responses by 5:00 pm on Tuesday, March 9th. Please feel free to reach out to any school administrator if you have questions.

post_text: Over the past few weeks, scholars at Stokes School - East End Campus have been learning about a number of heroes in American history, like Sarah Mapps Douglass, Carter G. post_text:
Last Friday the Black History Month team celebrated the DRUM CIRCLE. Mr. Ango dressed in regal African attire and showed a student friendly video that showed our scholars how children in Africa make their own toys and drums. Mr. Coley and Mr. Ango played the drums for our listening pleasure. This was followed by Mdme Sy and PreKF dancing in the drum circle to the drums. Scholars danced their way back to class.

This Friday scholars will learn that STEPPING originated in Africa. On Tuesday a parent will visit the classes with the Maya Angelou school steppers to demonstrate stepping and teach one or two steps to Stokes' scholars. On Friday Ms. Angela will show a video featuring "Gum Boots." Scholars will Show their Step Skills and will celebrate by stepping all the way to classrooms.

post_text: Stokes School - East End campus has partnered with the DC Department of Parks and Recreation Tennis Division to bring the US Tennis Association's NetGeneration Program to the school. USTA is donating equipment to the school and DCDPR is bringing training and curriculum to the PE staff to introduce tennis skills and fun exercise activities into PE on a weekly basis. DPR staff, including Stokes parent Jamal Hicks, came out to the school to do a tennis community outreach event and kids had FUN.

Join the Stokes Saturday Academy
The winter session of the Stokes Saturday Academy will begin on Saturday, January 26. The classes being offered this session include: Sign language for adults, French for adults, Jazz and Hip Hop for children and, Zumbini. Each session consists of five classes and costs $50. The classes must have eight participants so registering in a timely manner will guarantee your space. For more information and to register please go to: https://www.ewstokes.org/copy-of-saturday-academy.

post_text:
Just in time for holiday giving, A Place to Call School is the story of the first 20 years of the Elsie Whitlow Stokes Community Freedom Public Charter School and is a tribute to the school’s namesake. The book tells the story of how a talented and committed community of educators, volunteers and parents created a successful, sustainable urban elementary school that should become a model for public schools everywhere.
A Place to Call School is available for $25.00 at
http://ewstokes.corecommerce.com/Other/. Please specify "Book" when placing an order!

MLB Players Trust added 20 new photos to the album: 2018 Design Day — in Washington DC, USA.
October 2, 2018 at 4:01 PM · Vienna, VA ·

On July 13, The Players Trust announced a partnership with KaBOOM!; a national organization that builds playgrounds for children to have a safe and fun place to play. On September 5, the preschool Art class of Elsie Whitlow Stokes Community Freedom Public Charter School in Washington, D.C. designed their ideal playground!

That same afternoon, The Players Trust Buses for Baseball program provided tickets and transportation to the students and their families to attend the WAS vs STL game.

post_text: The Stokes School family came out today to help bring the vision of a playground at our East End campus to fruition. Thanks to Stokes School parents, staff, scholars, alumni and all of the Friends of Stokes who worked tirelessly to make this day happen. Special thanks to MLB Players Trust for sponsoring the build and to KaBOOM! for the support and guidance throughout the planning and build process. Our young scholars will be thrilled when they see their new playground next week!

post_text: Pre-K classes are learning how we express ourselves (individually and culturally) with clothes. As they prepare to get deep into the concept, they are starting by building vocabulary about clothes by asking questions like: What are the names of different kinds of clothes? How are clothes made? How are they cared for? Teachers are finding lots of ways for them to explore.

post_text: Here at Stokes School - East End, we share the historic Evans Middle School Building with two great schools with missions we appreciate, Maya Angelou Public Charter School and Maya Angelou Young Adult Learning Center. Yesterday, students from the high school came to do a PUPPET SHOW for our young scholars. This is the students' final project from their Art class, Black Broadway. How cool is that?

post_text:
We had our first Joyful Food Market this afternoon! There was an abundance of fresh produce for all Stokes families. Parents and scholars tasted salad samples and took recipes to try at home. Scholars had fun coloring and learning about different fruits and vegetables. Our friends from Maya Angelou PCS helped to distribute the food - and a good time was had by all!

We're looking forward to next month's market on November 1st from 3:30 pm-5:30 pm. All Stokes School East End families are encouraged to come!
Joyful Food Markets Maya Angelou Public Charter School
